04204nam a22005895i 9780822393672DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223936727 a10.1515/97808223936722doi  a(DE-B1597)554608  a(OCoLC)739839194  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aRD575b.S263 2011 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a617.4/610592095612221 aSanal, Aslihan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Organs Within Us :bTransplants and the Moral Economy /cAslihan Sanal. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b11 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExperimental futures : technological lives, scientific arts, anthropological voices00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue. The Accurate Nature of Things -- tIntroduction. What Makes the World Our Own -- tPart One. The Desirable -- tPart Two. The Impossible -- tConclusion. New Life -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew Organs Within Us is a richly detailed and conceptually innovative ethnographic analysis of organ transplantation in Turkey. Drawing on the moving stories of kidney-transplant patients and physicians in Istanbul, Aslihan Sanal examines how imported biotechnologies are made meaningful and acceptable not only to patients and doctors, but also to the patients' families and Turkish society more broadly. She argues that the psychological theory of object relations and the Turkish concept of benimseme-the process of accepting something foreign by making it one's own-help to explain both the rituals that physicians perform to make organ transplantation viable in Turkey and the psychic transformations experienced by patients who suffer renal failure and undergo dialysis and organ transplantation. Soon after beginning dialysis, patients are told that transplantable kidneys are in short supply; they should look for an organ donor. Poorer patients add their names to the state-run organ share lists. Wealthier patients pay for organs and surgeries, often in foreign countries such as India, Russia, or Iraq. Sanal links Turkey's expanding trade in illegal organs to patients' desires to be free from dialysis machines, physicians' qualms about declaring brain-death, and media-hyped rumors of a criminal organ mafia, as well as to the country's political instability, the privatization of its hospitals, and its position as a hub in the global market for organs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aKidneysxTransplantationxPatientszTurkey. 0aOrgan traffickingzTurkey. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etcxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etczTurkey. 0aTransplantation of organs, tissues, etc.xMoral and ethical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393672zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393672423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393672.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles